{{short description|Thai meditation method}}
{{good article}}
[[File:Thai woman meditating.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|alt=Thai young woman meditating|In Dhammakaya meditation, there are several techniques which can be used in focusing the attention on the center of the body.{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=238–9}}]]
{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}

'''Dhammakaya meditation''' is a method of [[Buddhist meditation]] developed and taught by the Thai meditation teacher [[Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro]] (1885–1959).{{refn|group=note|Some sources state 1884 as year of birth.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=23}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=52}}}} In Thailand, it is known as '''vijjā dhammakāya''', which translates as 'knowledge of the body of truth'. It is the meditation tradition that is at the center of the [[Dhammakaya Movement]]. The Dhammakaya meditation method has become very popular in Thailand and other parts of Southeast Asia, and has been described as a revival of ''[[samatha]]'' (tranquility) meditation in Thailand.

The method was discovered by Luang Pu Sodh in the 1910s. Followers of the Dhammakaya Movement believe the method was the same as the original method the Buddha used to attain [[enlightenment (Buddhism)|enlightenment]]. According to Luang Pu Sodh, the ''[[Dharmakāya#Dhammakaya Movement of Thailand|Dhammakāya]]'', the core concept of the tradition, can be found within every human being. The most important aspect of the meditation method is the focus on the center of the body. As of 2008, there was still scholarly debate as to the origins of Dhammakaya meditation. Scholars refer to the [[Yogavacara]] tradition as a possible source, or that the method might be new or partly new. Dhammakaya meditation is taught at several temples of the movement, and consists of a stage of ''samatha'' (tranquility) and ''vipassana'' (insight), following the structure of the [[Visuddhimagga]], a standard fifth-century [[Theravāda]] guide about meditation. In the method, the stages are described in terms of inner bodies ({{Lang-pi|kāya|italic=yes}}), but also in terms of [[jhana|meditative absorptions]] ({{lang-pi|jhānas|italic=yes}}).

Dhammakaya meditation has been the subject of considerable discussion among Buddhists as to its authenticity and efficacy, and also has been the subject of several scientific studies.

== History ==
=== Background ===
{{main|Buddhist modernism}}
In the 19th and early 20th-century Thailand, public perception of the practice of Buddhism changed. Originally, Thai people saw meditation mostly as a personal and quite esoteric practice. In response to threats of colonial powers, the Thai kings and the reformed [[Dhammayut]] fraternity attempted to modernize Buddhism, and strip Buddhist practice of its ritualized and mystical appearance. In this process, meditation was devalued among monastics as study was more valued.<!--177--> Education in Buddhist doctrine was standardized and centralized, as local meditation lineages gradually died out.<!--212, 227--> Meditation traditions responded by reforming their methods, and referring more to scripture in an attempt to establish orthodoxy and survive.<!--178---> Meditation became less esoteric,<!--212, 219--> as temples were pressured to practice the uniform meditation practice considered orthodox.<!--224-8-->{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=177–8, 212, 224–8}}

=== Origins ===
Temples that refer to Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro as their teacher have published several biographies about him. According to these biographies, the principles of Dhammakaya meditation were discovered by Luang Pu Sodh at Wat Botbon, in [[Nonthaburi Province]] on a full-moon night of the tenth lunar month, sometime in the 1910s.{{refn|There are differing timelines on when this occurred. Some scholars indicate 1915,{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=389}} others 1916{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=82}} or 1917.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Pichit|last1=Awirutthapanich|first2=Punchai|last2=Pantiya|year=2017|script-title=หลักฐาน ธรรมกายในคัมภีร์พุทธโบราณ ฉบับวิชาการ 1|trans-title=Dhammakaya Evidence in Ancient Buddhist Books, Academic Version 1|journal=Songklanakarin Journal of Social Sciences and Humanities|volume=23|issue=2|url=https://www.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/psujssh/article/view/102062}}</ref>|group=note}} Though he had practised several other forms of meditation in Thailand with well-known meditation teachers, he felt he had not yet accomplished the [[enlightenment (Buddhism)|enlightenment]] which the Buddha had experienced. That night, he decided to take a vow to meditate until he could at least accomplish some part of what the Buddha had once attained. He then experienced what followers consider a breakthrough in meditation.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=82}}

This breakthrough is described in the biographies as a deeper meaning to the [[Middle Way]], a teaching described in the [[Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta]], an early Buddhist [[sutra|discourse]]. This deeper meaning involves meditation technique.{{sfn|Dhammakāya Foundation|1996|page=46}}{{sfn|Taylor|2008|p=52}} Essential in this process is the "center of the body", which Luang Por Sodh precisely describes as being at a point two finger widths above the navel of each person: whatever technique someone might use to meditate, the mind can only attain a higher level of insight through this center. This center is also believed to play a fundamental role in the birth and death of an individual.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=84}} According to Luang Pu Sodh, the ''[[Dharmakāya#Dhammakaya Movement of Thailand|Dhammakaya]]'', the core concept of the tradition, can be found within every human being. It has the shape of a Buddha sitting within oneself.{{sfn|Tanabe|2016|p=127}} Followers of the [[Dhammakaya Movement]] believe that the Buddha became enlightened by using this method, and believe that knowledge of the method was lost five hundred years after the Buddha's death.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=82}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=76}} Temples of the movement refer to the [[Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta]] or the [[Visuddhimagga]] among others for Dhammakaya meditation's theoretical foundations.<ref name="Schedneck 2015">{{cite book|last1=Schedneck|first1=Brooke|title=Thailand's International Meditation Centers: Tourism and the Global Commodification of Religious Practices|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-1-317-44938-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o5lhCQAAQBAJ|date=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref name="Hutter 2016">{{cite book|editor-last1=Hutter|editor-first1=Manfred|editor-last2=Loseries|editor-first2=Andrea|editor-last3=Linder|editor-first3=Julia|editor-last4=Frasch|editor-first4=Tilman|editor-last5=Schicklgruber|editor-first5=Christian|last1=Hutter|first1=Manfred|encyclopedia=Theravāda-Buddhismus und Tibetischer Buddhismus|title=Buddhismus in Thailand und Laos|trans-title=Buddhism in Thailand and Laos|date=2016|publisher=Kohlhammer|isbn=3-17-028499-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=717EDQAAQBAJ|language=de|series=Buddhism|volume=II}}</ref>{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=249–50}}

Since the 2000s, scholars have brought forward new evidence that Luang Pu Sodh's approach may have roots in the Yogavacara tradition (also known as [[tantric Theravada|tantric Theravāda]]; not to be confused with the [[Yogachara|Yogacāra School]] in [[Mahāyāna Buddhism]]).{{sfn|Newell|2008|pages=256–7}}{{sfn|Williams|2009|p=327 n.73}}{{sfn|Crosby|2000|p=160}} During the revival and modernization of Thai Buddhism in the nineteenth and early twentieth century CE, Thai temples in the [[Maha Nikaya|Mahānikāya]] fraternity were forced to adjust to new reforms, including the meditation method used and taught.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=268}} In particular, leading monks in the Mahanikaya fraternity promoted the New Burmese method of [[U Nārada]] and [[Mahasi Sayadaw]]. The Dhammakaya meditation method managed to survive despite these pressures to reform.{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=268-70}} Therefore, Dhammakaya and ''Yogavacara'' meditation are both meditation forms that date back before these modernization efforts, and scholars have theorized that the two disciplines may share a common ancestry.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=95}} This ancestry would be related to Wat Rajasittharam, the temple where Luang Pu Sodh used to practice before he went on to develop Dhammakaya meditation.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=263}}{{sfn|Crosby|Skilton|Gunasena|2012|p=178 n.1}} An alternative theory suggests an origin in Tibetan or other forms of Mahāyāna Buddhism,{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=256}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=90–1}} but scholars C.S. Newell and Phibul Choompolpaisal believe a Yogavacara origin to be more likely. Newell notes that some aspects of Dhammakaya meditation cannot be found in Yogavacara practices, and theorizes that Dhammakaya meditation could have been "grafted onto an existing, preparatory system of concentration" and further developed.{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=256–7}}{{sfn|Skilton|Choompolpaisal|2017|page=87 n.10}} Theologian Rory Mackenzie does not draw any conclusions about the matter yet; he states that a Tibetan origin is unlikely, that a Yogavacara origin cannot yet be proven, and it is also "quite possible" that Luang Pu Sodh developed his approach through his own "psychic experiences".{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=113, 224 n.15}}

=== Development to the present day ===
After discovering the method of Dhammakaya meditation, Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro first taught it to others at Wat Bangpla, in [[Nakhon Pathom Province]].{{sfn|Dhammakāya Foundation|1996|p=48}} Luang Pu Sodh was given his first position as [[abbot]] at [[Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen]], a temple that has been associated with Dhammakaya meditation ever since. Luang Pu Sodh devoted the remainder of his life to teaching Dhammakaya meditation. In 1931, he set up what he called a 'meditation workshop' ({{lang-th|โรงงานทำวิชชา|translit=ronggan tham vicha}}) with meditation practitioners meditating in six-hour shifts throughout the day.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=32}} According to a textbook of one temple, the meditation workshop was reserved for gifted practitioners able to practice Dhammakaya meditation on a higher level.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=32}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|page=24}}{{sfn|Dhammakaya Open University|2010|p=139}} The purpose of the workshop was to use meditation to study certain subjects, which included understanding the nature of the world and the universe, "to learn the truth about the worlds and the galaxies".{{sfn|Dhammakaya Open University|2010|pp=39, 97}}

Since Luang Pu Sodh's death in 1959, Dhammakaya meditation has been taught by his students at several major temples, including Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen, [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]] in [[Pathum Thani Province|Pathum Thani]], [[Dhammakaya Movement#Wat Luang Phor Sodh Dhammakayaram|Wat Luang Por Sodh Dhammakayaram]] in [[Damnoen Saduak District]], [[Ratchaburi Province]], and [[Dhammakaya Movement#Wat Rajorasaram|Wat Rajorasaram]] in [[Bang Khun Thian District]], Bangkok, as well as in branch centers of these temples across and outside of Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dhammakaya.net/modules/centers/worldwide-centers|title=Worldwide Coordination centers|last=|first=|date=2016|website=|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|access-date=22 June 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=117–9, 235}}{{sfn|Schedneck|2016|pp=5–6}} Of these, Wat Phra Dhammakaya and Wat Luang Por Sodh Dhammakayaram have published instructive books on Dhammakaya meditation in English. Both also offer training retreats for the public.<ref name="Schedneck 2015" />{{sfn|Schedneck|2016|pp=5–6}} The method has become very popular in Thailand and other parts of Southeast Asia,{{sfn|McDaniel|2010|p=661}} and has been described as a revival of ''[[samatha]]'' (tranquility) meditation in Thailand.{{sfn|Bechert|1994|p=259}}

According to Newell, Dhammakaya meditation is taught more or less the same by each temple.<!--238--> However, the emphasis differs, with some temples being more esoteric about the method than others. For example, Wat Luang Phor Sod Dhammakayaram is more specific about the higher stages of meditation in their publications than Wat Phra Dhammakaya, while Wat Phra Dhammakaya emphasizes the calm and concentration the method brings.<!--246-8-->{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=238, 246–8}}

== Method ==
Dhammakaya meditation is also known as ''vijjā dhammakāya'', which translates as 'knowledge of the body of truth'.{{sfn|Rhys Davids|Stede|1921|loc=entries on ''Dhamma'', ''Vijjā'' and ''Kāya''}}

=== The ''samatha'' stage ===
[[File:Buddha topview.jpg|thumb|A topview of the Buddha, as visualized in Dhammakaya meditation]]
There are several techniques which can be used by practitioners in focusing the attention on the center of the body.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=82–4}}{{sfn|Zehner|2005|p=2325}}{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=389}} Practitioners may visualize a mental image at the center of the body–characteristically, a crystal ball or a crystal clear Buddha image.{{sfn|Tanabe|2016|p=127}} This has been compared with meditation on [[Kasina|a bright object]] in the Visuddhimagga.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=84}}{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=238}} Temples in the tradition often use crystal balls in meditation teaching, to the extent that the crystal ball has become a sacred symbol of the meditation tradition.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=14}}{{sfn|Chattinawat|2009|p=57}} Practitioners then visualize this image in front of themselves, and then move the mental image inwards through seven bases of the mind, that is:
# the nostril,
# the corner of the eye,
# the center of the head,
# the roof of the mouth,
# the center of the throat,
# the middle of the stomach at the level of the navel and
# two finger breadths above the previous point, where they keep their attention.
In this context, the center of the body is often called the "seventh base".<ref name="Hutter 2016" />{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=82}} In the tradition, the other six bases have a minor role, as they only function as reference points for the visualization. In this respect, the tradition's approach differs from the extensive symbolism of the ''[[cakra]]s'' as found in [[Vajrayana#Tibetan Buddhism|Tibetan Tantric tradition]], for example.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=108}}

At the same time, practitioners may use a ''[[mantra]]'' ({{lang-th|บริกรรมภาวนา|translit=borikam-phavana}}),<ref name="Hutter 2016" />{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=238}} that is ''Sammā-Arahaṃ'', which refers to the Buddha who has 'perfectly' (''sammā'') attained 'perfection in the Buddhist sense' (''[[Arhat|arahaṃ]]''),{{sfn|Rhys Davids|Stede|1921|loc=entries on ''Sammā'' and ''Arahant''|pp=76, 695}}{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=389}} as can be found in the traditional [[Buddhist chant#Theravada chants|''Tiratanavanda'' chant]]. This is a form of ''[[Buddhanusmrti|Buddhanussati]]'', i.e. recollecting the Buddha qualities. This mantra has also been used by monks from Northern Thailand.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=238}} Alternatively, according to Wat Phra Dhammakaya, practitioners can also place the attention at the center of the body directly,{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=113}} and can even do so without visualizing or using a mantra.<ref>{{cite book|title=Start Meditation Today|edition= 3rd|publisher=[[Dhammakaya Foundation]]|year=2016|pages=53–4|url=http://interhq.org/download/book/english/start_meditation_today%20_en.pdf|isbn=974-87855-4-8}}</ref>

The types of practices, such as use of a mantra and use of a bright object, are not unique to Dhammakaya meditation, but the details of the technique are.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=238}} As with many forms of Buddhist meditation, Dhammakaya meditation has both ''samatha'' and ''vipassana'' stages.{{sfn|Tanabe|2016|pp=127–8}} As is common with traditional ''samatha'' practice, the goal of Dhammakaya meditation at the ''samatha'' level is to overcome [[five hindrances|mental hindrances to concentration]].{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=390}} When the mind becomes peaceful and stable during ''samatha'', it overcomes those hindrances and reaches a state of concentration. The indication of reaching this stage is that a bright light will arise at the center of the body.{{sfn|Tanabe|2016|p=128}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=80}} The mind should then be directed continuously at the center of this sphere helping to transport the mind towards an inner path with several stages.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=239}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|page=102}} During these stages, the practitioner may experience goose bumps or other physical responses. Known as ''[[pīti]]'', this phenomenon is understood to be temporary.{{sfn|Skilton|Choompolpaisal|2017|page=94 n.21}}[[File:The eighteen bodies (kayas) of Vijja Dhammakaya.jpg|thumb|The nine pairs of bodies (''kāyas'') in Vijjā Dhammakāya.]]

The process of concentration in Dhammakaya meditation correlates with the description of ''samatha'' meditation in the Visuddhimagga, specifically ''kasina'' meditation.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=256}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=80}}{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=84}} Once the mental hindrances are overcome, the visual image imagined is transformed.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=80}} The first stage of this path Luang Pu Sodh simply called the 'beginning of the path' ({{lang-th|translit=pathommamak|ปฐมมรรค}}).{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=84}}{{sfn|Zehner|2005|p=2325}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=102}}
After that, Luang Pu Sodh would usually describe the level of attainment in terms of inner bodies (''{{lang-pi|kāya}}'') within every human being,{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=83}} which are successively more subtle, and come in pairs. Mackenzie compares this with [[Russian doll]]s nestled within each other.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=103, 107, 113}} These bodies indicate to what extent the practitioner has attained in meditation practice. Each of these bodies is preceded by several spheres of light.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=239}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=103}} In total, every human being consists of nine types of bodies,{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=87|loc=Diagram 4}}{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=240–1}} each of which has a normal and refined form.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=103|quote="... as with the previous bodies, these bodies have both a normal and refined form."}} The first four pairs of these bodies are equated with the orthodox ''[[jhāna]]'' meditation attainments.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=102–3}} The final four of these inner pairs are called the ''Dhammakayas'' and are equated with the [[four stages of enlightenment]], leading to the final stage of enlightenment (''arahant'').{{sfn|Newell|2008|pp=240–1}}{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=390}} In between is the 'change-of-lineage' ({{lang-pi|gotrabhū|italic=yes}}) intermediary Dhammakaya state:{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=103}}{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=240}} this is the intermediate state between not being enlightened yet and the four stages of enlightenment.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=85, 87|loc=Diagram 4}}

The attainment of the ''Dhammakaya'' (or ''Dhammakayas'') is thus described as the result of many steps of practice, culminating in the cessation of the [[Kilesa|defilements]] in the mind, or, in positive terms, as the highest happiness. The ''Dhammakaya'' is considered the "purest element" within every human being, which is permanent and essential, and is equated with [[Nirvana (Buddhism)|Nirvana]].{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=79–80}} The purest element has the shape of a luminous Buddha figure sitting within oneself.{{sfn|Williams|2009|p=126}} Besides the unorthodox definition of Nirvana as true happiness, permanent and essential, it is also described by the movement from a more orthodox perspective, as the absence of [[lobha|greed]], [[Dvesha (Buddhism)|hatred]] and [[Moha (Buddhism)|delusion]].{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=80}} Religion scholar Rachelle Scott, however, has argued that the positive description of Nirvana as happiness, permanent and essential, is what has contributed to the popularity of the method and its proponents.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=80}}

