=== The ''vipassana'' stage ===
Dhammakaya meditation begins with the ''vipassana'' level at a later stage than some other meditation schools in Thailand.{{sfn|Cousins|1996|pp=38–9}} In Dhammakaya meditation, a distinction is made between "seeing the Dhammakāya" and "being the Dhammakāya". Only the latter is equated with having attained the stages of enlightenment at a stable level. It is believed that the further practitioners progress through the successive stages of the practice, the more their mind will become more pure and refined.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=85}} After practitioners have attained the ''Dhammakaya'', they can gain insight into the reality of life through observation of their own physical and mental processes.{{sfn|Tanabe|2016|p=128}} It is believed they can understand birth, death and suffering at a deeper level,<!--85--> when they see the literal essence of these phenomena through meditative attainment.<!--88--> The practitioner can accomplish a purification of the mind<!--85--> until an end can be reached, that is Nirvana.<!--87-->{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=85–8}} Nirvana is described as a subtle sphere ({{lang-pi|ayatana|italic=yes}}) and, controversially, as [[atman (Buddhism)|"true self"]] ({{lang-pi|attā|italic=yes}}). Orthodox teachings on [[anatta|not-self]] ({{lang-pi|anattā|italic=yes}}) are regarded as methods to let go of what is not the true self.{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=390}}

Dhammakaya meditation at the higher levels is believed to bring forth ''[[abhiñña]]'', mental powers. Through such powers practitioners are believed to be able to see different realms of the cosmos following [[Buddhist cosmology]].{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=241}} These powers can also be used for the benefit of society at large.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=34–5}}{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=241}} Dhammakaya meditation is believed by some practitioners to have been used during the Second World War to prevent Thailand from being bombed,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|editor1-last=Jerryson|editor1-first=Michael|year=2016|encyclopedia=The Oxford Handbook of Contemporary Buddhism|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=978-0-19-936238-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rBk1DQAAQBAJ|title=Contemporary Thai Buddhism|last=Scott|first=Rachelle M.|page=203}}</ref>{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=34–5}} and used to extinguish the negative forces in the cosmos ([[Mara (demon)|Māra]]).<ref name="Falk 2007">{{cite book|last1=Falk |first1=Monica Lindberg|title=Making fields of merit: Buddhist female ascetics and gendered orders in Thailand|date=2007|publisher=NIAS Press|location=Copenhagen|isbn=978-87-7694-019-5|edition= 1st|page=182}}</ref>{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=390}} This belief that Dhammakaya meditation can be used to extinguish negative forces has strongly affected the attitudes of practitioners at Dhammakaya movement temples, who therefore hold that Dhammakaya meditation is not only important for the individual, but also for the {{em|cosmos}} at large.<ref name="Hutter 2016" />{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|pp=32–3}}

== Discussion and research ==
{{See also|Dhammakaya Movement#Dhammakaya meditation and True Self}}
[[File:School children meditating.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|left|alt=Thai school children meditating as part of organized activities at the school.|Thai school children meditating as part of organized activities at school.]]
Scientific research done on Dhammakaya meditation at the ''samatha'' level has shown that it reduced serum [[cortisol]] level and blood pressure,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Khobragade|first1=Yadneshwar|last2=Khobragade|first2=Sujata|last3=Abbas|first3=Adinegara|title=Hypertension and meditation: can meditation be useful in preventing hypertension?|journal=International Journal of Community Medicine and Public Health|date=2016|page=1691|doi=10.18203/2394-6040.ijcmph20162030}}</ref>{{sfn|Sudsuang|Chentanez|Veluvan|1990|page=544}} while increasing serum protein level. [[Systolic pressure]], [[diastolic pressure]] and pulse rate were also reduced, as well as tidal capacity, tidal volume and maximal voluntary ventilation. Finally, reaction time was reduced.{{sfn|Sudsuang|Chentanez|Veluvan|1990|pp=544–5}} Psychologically, Dhammakaya meditation reduced clinical depression.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kasantikul|last2=Suttipan|last3=Worakul|year=1986|title=Title unknown|journal=Journal of the Psychiatric Association of Thailand|volume=31|pages=177–90}}</ref>

According to Scott, in the time of Luang Pu Sodh the method was criticized by some for being extra-canonical,{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=82}} although Asian studies scholar Edwin Zehner downplays this, stating there was no widespread criticism.{{sfn|Zehner|2005|p=2324}} Discussion within the Thai monastic community led to an inspection at Wat Paknam, but no fault could be found in Luang Pu Sodh's method.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=24}} More recently, Dhammakaya meditation has been depicted as a fast and effective meditation method for competitive professionals with little time.{{sfn|Newell|2008|p=242}}{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=65}} Mackenzie does remark, however, that the method is not simpler than other methods, but that its appeal is that its benefits can be more readily experienced than more orthodox models.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=65}} As with other meditation methods emphasizing ''samatha'', opponents writing from a [[Buddhist modernism|modernist]] standpoint have criticized the method. These critics point at the emphasis on pleasant feelings as opposed to insight. They argue against the mystical dimension of meditation practice, saying that bliss in meditation is a hindrance to insight. On the other hand, practitioners of the method often argue how the method is capable of changing people for the better, and has positive effects in all aspects of the practitioner's daily life.{{sfn|Scott|2009|p=81–2}} Religion scholar Donald Swearer calls the meditation method "a unique method of meditation which involves a visualization technique not unlike that associated with certain [[yogic]] or tantric forms of meditation, and is easily taught to large groups of people".{{sfn|Swearer|1991|p=660}} Meditation in large groups, as is common in the activities of Wat Phra Dhammakaya, contrasts with the emphasis of most Thai temples on meditation in solitude. The temple stresses the importance of meditating as a group to counterbalance the negativity in the world.{{sfn|Litalien|2010|p=159}}

The interpretations of the true self by the Dhammakaya movement have been criticized by orthodox Thai scholars such as [[Prayudh Payutto|Phra Payutto]], and have led to considerable debate in Thailand. {{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=390}} The word ''dhammakāya'' in its orthodox sense is commonly understood as a figurative term, meaning the "body" or the sum of the Buddha's teachings.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reynolds|first=Frank E.|year=1977|title=The Several Bodies of Buddha: Reflections on a Neglected Aspect of Theravada Tradition|journal=History of Religions |volume=16 |issue=4 |jstor=1062637 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Several_Bodies_of_Buddha_Reflections.html?id=KvQ4jwEACAAJ|pp=376–7}}</ref>{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=89}} The idea of a body of spiritual attainment can be found in the [[Pali Canon|early Buddhist scriptures]], though, but this is described as a "body accomplished by the mind" ({{lang-pi|manomayakāya|italic=yes}}) and not directly connected with the attainment of Nirvana.<!--89--> However, in a later Sinhalese [[Pāli]] text, Nirvana is described as a "body of emptiness", which is a similar concept. Finally, the concept of the [[Dharmakāya]] has been much further developed in Mahāyāna Buddhism.<!--90-->{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|p=90}} The interpretations of the Dhammakaya movement with regard to true self have been compared with [[Mahāyāna]] ideas like the [[Buddha Nature]],{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=390}} but such influence has been rejected by the movement itself.{{sfn|Williams|2009|pp=126–7}} Proponents of the movement cite several Pāli texts, such as one text stating that Nirvana is true happiness, and argue that the true self is a logical conclusion that follows from these texts. Other proponents feel that the problem is a matter of practice more than debate.{{sfn|Fuengfusakul|1998|pp=92–3}}<ref name="Rungrawee 2002">{{cite journal|last1=Chalermsripinyorat|first1=Rungrawee|title=Doing the Business of Faith: The Capitalistic Dhammakaya Movement and the Spiritually-thirsty Thai Middle Class|journal=Manusya: Journal of Humanities|date=2002|volume=5|issue=1|pages=14–20|url=http://www.manusya.journals.chula.ac.th/files/essay/rungrawee_13-28.pdf}}</ref>

